Question: What is the maximum amount of pecuniary penalties the ECB may impose
  on a supervised entity for a breach?
Example answer: The ECB may impose pecuniary penalties of up to twice the amount of
  the profits gained or losses avoided because of the breach, or up to
  10% of the supervised entity's total annual turnover in the
  preceding business year. When deciding on the amount of the penalty,
  the ECB applies its Guide to the method of setting administrative
  pecuniary penalties, and the penalties imposed must be effective,
  proportionate and dissuasive. (ECB Supervisory Manual, page 107)
