Question: Under what condition does a bank migrate from SI to LSI status, and is
  one-time non-fulfilment of the criteria sufficient?
Example answer: A bank changes status from LSI to SI when at least one of the
  significance criteria is met, but migration from SI to LSI status is
  not triggered by a one-time failure to meet any of the significance
  criteria. According to the SSMFR, the bank must fall short of the
  relevant criteria for three consecutive calendar years in order to
  qualify for reclassification, although it is possible to diverge
  from this rule if justified by exceptional circumstances stipulated
  in the SSMFR. (ECB Supervisory Manual, page 60)
Predicted answer: Condition for migration: an institution migrates from Significant
  Institution (SI) to Less Significant Institution (LSI) only if it
  falls short of the relevant significance criteria for three
  consecutive calendar years (the "three‑year rule") (ECB Supervisory
  Manual, pp. 61–62).  Is one‑time non‑fulfilment sufficient? No — a
  one‑time or non‑persistent failure to meet the criteria is
  insufficient to trigger migration. A departure from the three‑year
  requirement is only possible in exceptional circumstances as set out
  in the SSM Framework Regulation (SSMFR).
