Score: 0.98

Question: Who are the members of a Joint Supervisory Team and how is its size
  determined?
Example answer: JSTs comprise staff from both the ECB and the NCAs of the countries in
  which the SIs, including their banking subsidiaries or significant
  cross-border branches, are established, and a JST is established for
  each SI at the highest level of consolidation. The size, overall
  composition and organisation of a JST varies depending on the
  nature, complexity, scale, business model and risk profile of the
  supervised entity. (ECB Supervisory Manual, page 9)
Predicted answer: Who the JST members are - JSTs comprise staff from both the ECB and
  the relevant national competent authorities (NCAs) for the
  jurisdictions where the significant institution (SI) and its
  subsidiaries/branches are established. - Key roles within a JST:   -
  JST coordinator (ECB-appointed).   - NCA local coordinators
  (representing and reflecting their NCA views).   - A team of experts
  (ECB and NCA specialists assigned to the JST). - For banks with a
  significant multi‑Member‑State presence there is a “core JST”
  chaired by the JST coordinator and composed of the local
  coordinators of the relevant NCAs. - On‑site inspection teams are
  organisationally independent but work closely with the relevant JST.
  What JSTs do (relevant to membership) - Day‑to‑day off‑site
  supervision at consolidated, sub‑consolidated and solo levels. -
  Drafting and organising the Supervisory Examination Programme and
  allocating tasks. - Carrying out SREP, suitability assessments and
  coordinating on‑site activity. - JSTs operate within ECB supervisory
  directorates (DG/SIB, DG/UDI and DG/SPL) and are supported by ECB
  horizontal and specialised divisions.  How JST size and composition
  are determined - The size, overall composition and organisation of a
  JST “varies depending on the nature, complexity, scale, business
  model and risk profile” of the supervised entity. - JST coordinators
  are appointed for three to five years; JST members are expected to
  rotate regularly. - No numeric staffing minima/maxima, fixed quotas
