Question: How does the ECB cooperate with the EBA on EU-wide stress tests, and
  what kind of stress-testing exercises does ECB Banking Supervision
  run in years where no EU-wide stress test takes place?
Example answer: In cooperation with the ESRB, the EBA is responsible for the
  initiation and overall coordination of EU-wide assessments of the
  resilience of credit institutions, while the ECB is in charge of
  carrying out the assessments within the participating Member States
  with the support of the NCAs. In years when there are no EU-wide
  stress tests, ECB Banking Supervision conducts thematic stress tests
  focusing on specific supervisory priorities, such as interest rate
  risk in the banking book in 2017, liquidity risk in 2019, climate
  risk in 2022, and cyber resilience in 2024. (ECB Supervisory Manual,
  pages 36, 72)
Predicted answer: 1) Cooperation with the EBA on EU‑wide stress tests - The EBA, in
  cooperation with the ESRB, initiates and overall coordinates the
  two‑yearly EU‑wide stress‑test exercises. - The ECB contributes to
  these system‑wide exercises via its Stress Test Experts Division,
  which performs horizontal microprudential tasks: designing
  methodology and templates, quality assurance, challenging banks’
  projections, and supervising models and IT. - The ECB cooperates
  with the EBA and national competent authorities (NCAs) where
  appropriate, and the stress‑test results feed into the ECB’s SREP
  (supervisory review and evaluation process).  2) What the ECB runs
  in years without an EU‑wide EBA exercise - In non‑EBA years the ECB
  conducts thematic stress tests focused on supervisory priorities.
  Examples given: interest‑rate‑risk in the banking book (2017);
  liquidity risk (2019); climate risk (2022); cyber resilience (2024).
  - The ECB also runs targeted desk‑top vulnerability analyses in
  response to unforeseen developments (examples: 2020 and 2022). -
  Microprudential stress‑testing exercises are often complemented by
  top‑down macroprudential extensions when needed.
