Question: Could you clarify the conceptual difference between supervisory
  enforcement measures and sanctions, and which ECB body is
  responsible for investigating suspected breaches by significant
  institutions?
Example answer: Enforcement measures aim to compel supervised entities to comply with
  prudential requirements laid down in regulation, national law
  implementing an EU directive or a decision, while sanctions aim to
  punish supervised entities for failing to comply with prudential
  requirements and to deter future breaches. The Independent
  Investigating Unit, whose tasks fall under the remit of the
  Enforcement and Sanctions Division, is responsible for investigating
  alleged breaches of directly applicable EU law, including ECB
  supervisory decisions or regulations, committed by significant
  institutions. (ECB Supervisory Manual, pages 104, 106)
Predicted answer: - Conceptual difference   - Supervisory enforcement measures:
  remedial/preventive supervisory acts intended to secure compliance
  (e.g., require an institution to take specified measures). They are
  aimed at remedying or preventing breaches and can be effected
  directly by the ECB or by instructing national competent authorities
  (NCAs) to use their national enforcement powers. Typical triggers
  include an existing breach, evidence that a breach will occur within
  the next 12 months, or other supervisory triggers.   - Sanctions:
  punitive administrative penalties whose purpose is to punish
  failures and deter future breaches. Sanctioning proceedings may be
  brought by the ECB or through NCAs; they can be initiated even after
  the underlying breach has ceased, subject to applicable limitation
  periods.  - Investigation responsibility   - Investigations of
  alleged breaches by significant institutions are carried out by the
  Independent Investigating Unit (IU) within the Enforcement and
  Sanctions Division. The IU investigates, grants the right to be
  heard, and prepares proposals (draft decisions) for the Supervisory
  Board.  - Applicable framework (as cited)   - SSM Regulation:
  Articles 9 and 18   - SSM Framework Regulation (SSMFR): Articles
  120–137   - Council Regulation on the ECB’s sanctioning powers   -
  ECB Supervisory Manual (pp. 103–107)
Rationale: Recall score: 0.95, sources score: 1.0, length score: 0.46.
Score: 0.87

Question: To which authority must an institution apply for a banking
  authorisation in a participating Member State, and on what basis is
  the application assessed?
Example answer: An application for a banking authorisation has to be submitted to the
  national competent authority of the Member State in which the
  institution is to be established and must be in accordance with the
  requirements set out in the relevant national legislation. This
  application is assessed to ensure that only entities that fulfil the
  applicable national and EU legal requirements enter the market as
  credit institutions. (ECB Supervisory Manual, page 49)
Predicted answer: - To whom to apply: the institution must apply to the national
  competent authority (NCA) of the Member State in which it is to be
  established.  - Who decides:   - Significant institutions (SIs): the
  ECB (direct supervision/authorisation responsibility).   - Less
  significant institutions (LSIs): the relevant NCA (NCAs retain
  direct responsibility).  - Legal basis and assessment:   -
  Applications are assessed under the applicable national legislation
  and EU law, notably the SSM legal framework (SSM Regulation/SSMFR)
  together with CRD IV/CRR.   - Typical assessment criteria include
  compliance with initial capital requirements, the fitness and
  propriety of the management and key function holders, the adequacy
  and viability of the business plan, and compliance with prudential
  requirements (capital, liquidity, governance, organizational
  arrangements, etc.).  Note: the retrieved excerpts confirm these
  allocation and high-level assessment principles but do not provide
  detailed numeric thresholds or a complete, itemized checklist of all
  authorisation requirements.
